observations.recommendation:
City Accountant to:

maintain subsidiary ledger cards for roads and road components for every road network;
prepare lapsing schedule showing the computation of the depreciation of each component of the Road Network System account;
disclose the total Road Network System account in the Notes to the Financial Statements; and 
make the necessary adjusting entries on repair and maintenance recorded to Road Network System account.

We recommended that Management direct the:
City Treasurer to coordinate with the City Accountant to account for the ₱446,592 balances as of December 31, 2020 from LBP;
City Treasurer to immediately submit to the Office of the City Accountant the Disbursement Vouchers and its supporting documents to take up unrecorded disbursements or proof that errors were indeed committed by bank to adjust the allegedly bank errors totaling ₱11.80 million;
City Accountant to record in the appropriate agency books the journal entry to take up returned check deposits totaling ₱453,796, to restore the Receivables account or revert the Income account and establish the liability of the taxpayer, whichever is applicable;
City Accountant to prepare and record the adjusting journal entry in the appropriate agency books to revert back to the appropriate funds the stale checks totaling ₱5.05 million and establish the liability of the City;
City Accountant to record the appropriate journal entries to take up the Debit and Credit Memos, deposit in transit, and unrecorded deposits totaling ₱4.60 million; and
City Accountant to exert more effort by assigning one personnel who shall reevaluate the previous BRSs to track down the unreconciled difference totaling to ₱3.09 million reported as deductions from bank balances.

We recommended that both the Local Chief Executive and the City Accountant disapprove additional cash advances to DOs/SDOs unless previous ones have been settled.
We also recommended that Management:
direct all SDOs to maintain individual cash books for periodic examination by the auditors;
direct the AOs to secure sufficient amount of fidelity bonds;
require the City Accountant to adjust and use the appropriate account name for each type of cash advance;
direct the City Accountant to require the AO of cash advances to provide an itemized list/net amount of payroll/budget of expenses as basis in computing the amount of cash advance; and
stop the practice of granting cash advances without supporting documents and on procurement activities, and to comply with the direct payment scheme or payment by check in consonance with one of the principles of imprest system which is all payments must be made by check.

We recommended that Management require the City Accountant to:
direct the Accountable Officers concerned to immediately cause for the liquidation of cash advances totaling ₱32.32 million as of December 31, 2020;
send letters to the concerned officers and employees demanding the immediate settlement/liquidation of their outstanding cash advances through the submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports and enforce the withholding of salary, in accordance with Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 if no action is taken after the lapse of the timeline set in the demand letter;
recommend to the City Mayor the disapproval of additional cash advance for travel and training and special purpose to personnel and Special Disbursing Officers, respectively with unliquidated cash advances unless the previous cash advance/s is/are fully settled;
monitor and establish controls to ensure the timely liquidation of cash advances through updated monthly aging of the same to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances; and
reconcile the GL balance of cash advance totaling ₱32.32 million with the SL balance at year end.

We recommended that Management:
require the City Accountant to provide Real Property Ledger Card for each real property (land) to record the property description, location, acquisition cost, additions and disposition;
require the GSO to provide Property Card for Land wherein the acquisition, description, custody, disposal and other information about the property are recorded;
require both the City Accountant and GSO to reconcile the ₱68.22 million difference between the inventory report and the accounting records of the land account, as well as the 2019 inventory of 147 lots as compared to identified 68 lots in 2020;
trace records/documents of the 68 parcels of land with incomplete data as to acquisition date and cost;
facilitate the preparation of documentary requirements to secure the TCT under the name of the City of Iriga for all parcels of land to support claims of ownership and to avoid loss of properties in case other interested parties may claim the same in the future; and
include in the ensuing years’ budget the fund required required to expedite the application for the land titles under the name of the City.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the:
Accounting Office to coordinate with the GSO in order to facilitate the recording of the parcels of land in the name of the City and reconcile the Inventory List of Land;
GSO and OCPDC-ZHALUD to facilitate the titling of the parcels of land used in the Housing Projects; and
OCPDC-ZHALUD to:
expedite the titling of the lots which were already  fully paid by the beneficiaries;
maintain a complete list of transferred Land Titles for reference;
generate an Inventory of Lands for Socialized Housing and Inventory of Idle Lands that can feasibly be used for future housing and resettlement sites;
update the Masterlist of the Socialized Housing Beneficiaries;
review and update the legitimacy of the awarded and unoccupied housing/lot unit; and
award the vacant housing/lot units to new qualified and legitimate beneficiaries.
review the legality of the current residents not originally awarded with the housing/lot units and appropriately secure contracts with the same; and
j.    create a master list of potential beneficiaries of local housing project of the City.

We recommended that Management require the City Treasurer to:
update the database wherein complete information of the capitalization, annual gross receipts, and other relevant data of business establishments of the City is stored;
endeavor to come up with complete database of business establishments thru regular tax mapping and coordination with barangays which have records/information of existing businesses within their jurisdictions;
generate complete List of Delinquent Business Establishment Taxpayers to facilitate the demand and collection of the business taxes in arrears;
explore the Enhanced Tax Revenue, Assessment and Collection System (ETRACS) in order that generated reports and information furnished to users and decision makers be reflective of the exact raw data from the automated system; and
continue efforts and activities that contribute to the realization and attainment of the target collections while undertaking necessary measures to maximize revenue from business taxes.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
require the different offices/end-users in the agency to prepare and submit their PPMPs incorporating therein all their procurement requirements for the year and have them duly evaluated and reviewed for consolidation by the BAC Secretariat into a comprehensive, workable and realistic APP which would reflect the details of the procurement activities that the agency seeks to undertake within the calendar year;
require the BAC to strictly follow the procurement methods and activities as stated in their APP;
comply with the documentary requirements on Shopping and SVP if these methods are being adopted; and
ensure compliance with Section 10 of R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR, that all procurement shall be undertaken through competitive bidding as the default mode or primary method of procurement so that the most advantageous price for the LGU is obtained.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
require the personnel involved to submit the supporting documents under City Ordinance No. 2020-09;
remind immediate supervisors of the responsibility in signing DTRs, i.e. certifying that entries are true and correct;
require the City Accountant in coordination with the Internal Audit Services to ensure completeness of the required support documents prior the disbursements to avoid doubtful transactions; and
cause the refund of hazard pay claims in excess of the actual service rendered.

City Accountant to:

maintain subsidiary ledger cards for roads and road components for every road network;
prepare lapsing schedule showing the computation of the depreciation of each component of the Road Network System account;
disclose the total Road Network System account in the Notes to the Financial Statements; and
make the necessary adjusting entries on repair and maintenance recorded to Road Network System account.

We recommended that Management:
ensure that cash advances shall be used solely for the specific legal purpose for which these are granted;
stop granting unauthorized cash advances to employees not designated as disbursing officers and non-employees of the City;
require the OIC-City Accountant to monitor liquidation of cash advances by observing the timeline set for each type of cash advance, ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of the year, and institute withholding of salary of those non-compliant; and
refrain from giving benefits and incentives to public school teachers other than those enumerated in COA Circular No. 2013-003 or unless provided with legal basis to forestall disallowance in audit.

We recommended that Management direct the:
OIC–City Budget Officer to report to the Local School Board (LSB) the unobligated balance of the appropriations at year-end;
City Treasurer to report to the LSB the available SEF as of given date;
LSB to observe the allocation of the priority projects, programs and activities chargeable against the SEF as net of the budgetary provision for the same or related item(s) in the budget for the DepEd and the ECCD Council, in compliance to Section 4 of the Local Government Code and the DEPED, DBM and DILG Joint Circular (JC) No. 1; and
LSB to consider the unobligated balance as well as the available fund as of year-end in the preparation and approval of the SEF Budget in the ensuing year.
